    <h3>Hypotheses & Most Dangerous Assumptions</h3>
    <p>From the opportunities in my experience map, I outlined four solutions: a locally-available wine list, a wine education tool, a stronger retail environment utilizing virtual reality, and marketing tools for wine producers.</p>
    <p>As the wine list and the retail environments solved for more critical user anxieties and obstacles problems, so I focused on those. To further clarify, I outlined my most dangerous assumptions, user groups,  and what each prototype would and would not be explicitly testing for.</p>
    <p>The prototyping process is a series of small experiments in which the designer uses artifacts to elicit new information about users‚Äô as well as test key elements of their proposed solution. Both of my prototypes were designed to do both of those things, and ultimately succeeded by eliciting new insights about the industry and user experience, as well as validating and invalidating core value propositions.</p>
